Communism returns in Russia
Moscow—More than a year ago, while on leave from the university where I was teaching in the United States, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of free speech.
But there is still some freedom preserved here.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country in an effort to win support from politicians not under the control of the Kremlin.
Protesters took to the streets.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate within the country.
Journalists and analysts do not necessarily follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely regarded as a product of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protest movement he initiated has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was dissolved on charges of "extremism," and its members are currently facing exile or investigation.
Almost every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent organizations are added to the "foreign agents" list — and even worse — labeled as "undesirable."
In the past year, Russia has been in a non-free state, which, although not far off, has been very intense.
For example, the law designating "foreign agents" was enacted in 2012, aimed at undermining or discrediting organizations or individuals engaged in "political activities" while also receiving funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where forwarding tweets is now considered a justification for labeling someone as a "foreign agent."
The "undesirable" label can lead to complete dissolution.
In just this year alone, the "foreign agents" list has seen an unprecedented increase of 101 entities.
Of the total of 359, 88 are media-related entities and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be listed on the registry because they "influence national politics."
But the core objective of journalism and propaganda is certainly to influence politics.
And this is precisely the issue: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he perceives criticism as a threat to his survival.
Although having endured all this silence and persecution, it is a group that is hardly likely to be an opposition force—Communist Party—that has survived and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This has largely been due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy—namely, urging people to support the forces most likely to defeat the candidates backed by the Kremlin—while the Communist Party has shown strong performance in both the recent parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party secured nearly 49.8%.
But the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the voting outcome had been manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, the Communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the Communists of old.
They not only do not deny the pleasures of the world, but party members instead dress in fur coats, enjoy traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires—such as the charismatic agricultural chief Pavlo Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's elections).
Although the party is still led by the 77-year-old Gennady Zyuganov, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger party members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko, for example.
Nikolai Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister claimed that Russians should be able to "eat better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded on his YouTube channel his efforts to prove the minister wrong.
Despite being threatened with disqualification, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the State Duma elections last month.
Although he received support from Navalny's "smart voting" system, he still lost to the candidate from United Russia.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a headline for a protest activity accusing "the state and government of taking over United Russia."
And then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudashova.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains — and is becoming increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the "smart voting" system, another rising star, the elegant Yekaterina Ngalichyeva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
It is ironic that the modernization of the Communist Party reflects a yearning for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the country that achieved these ideals was strict, it was not devoid of justice and mercy.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which an individual's eccentricity would not affect everyone.
Exactly based on this logic, all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "unified Russia" that can challenge Putin.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences and formed a common coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead the new government together with another opposition alliance.
Just as Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also prepare a unified electoral list for next year's parliamentary elections and field a single candidate for the position of prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic regime, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition.
While toppling Putin is far more difficult, it is not hard to foresee more measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party comprehensively.
But the above approach also brings risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims that Russian democracy "has not died out," and points to the country's "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he at least still has an interest in pretending that Russia has not been led toward near-authoritarianism.
Putin stated that he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin were to create and enforce rules capriciously, as it has with Russian liberals, driving the Communist Party underground, social explosion would be more likely to occur.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Communist Party members—yes, the Communists—could become an undeniable force.
